FieldDefinitionBuilder.GeoWithinBox methods have only 2 parameters for bounding box coordinates - x and y. It is impossible to add second corner coordinates.

Calling method creates query like this:
{code:title=Bad query|borderStyle=solid}
"$query" : {
        "Location" : {
                "$geoWithin" : {
                        "$box" : [
                                16.9,
                                52.38
                        ]
                }
        }
}
{code}

It results in throwing an exception by mongod:
{code}
"exception" : "Can't canonicalize query: BadValue bad geo query: { $geoWithin: { $box: [ 16.9, 52.38 ] } }",
"exceptionCode" : 17287,
{code}

According to DB documentation, $box should contain two pairs of coordinates, eg.
{code}
{ $box:  [ [ 0, 0 ], [ 100, 100 ] ] }
{code}

Given this schema:

{code}
> db.foo.find().pretty()
{
        "_id" : 1,
        "bars" : [
                {
                        "x" : 1,
                        "y" : 2
                },
                {
                        "x" : 2,
                        "y" : 3
                },
                {
                        "x" : 1,
                        "y" : 4
                }
        ]
}
{code}

and these classes:
{code}
        private class Foo
        {
            public int Id;

            public List<Bars> Bars;
        }

        private class UnwoundFoo
        {
            public int Id;
            [BsonElement("Bars")]
            public Bar Bar;
        }

        private class Bar
        {
            [BsonElement("x")]
            public int X;
            [BsonElement("y")]
            public int Y;
        }
{code}

The following aggregation query results in a NRE:

{code}
    var list = await col.Aggregate()
                .Unwind<Foo, UnwoundFoo>(x => x.Bars)
                .Match(x => x.Bar.X == 1)
                .Project(x => new { X = x.Bar.X, Y = x.Bar.Y })
                .ToListAsync();
{code}

Given the class and enum:

{code}
class Person
{
	public Color FavoriteColor { get; set; }
}

enum Color
{
	Blue,
	SomethingElse
}
{code}

The following code snippet will not work:

{code}
Builders<Person>.IndexKeys.Ascending(x => x.FavoriteColor);
Builders<Person>.Filter.Eq(x => x.FavoriteColor, Color.Blue);
// other builders as well
{code}

h4. Workaround

Use the string field name of the member. Even if you have mapped it to a different element name, as long as the member name is used, it will still get mapped:

{code}
Builders<Person>.IndexKeys.Ascending("FavoriteColor");
{code}
